{{Short description|Feminist movement, 2010s–present}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}
{{Use Oxford spelling|date=December 2017}}
{{Feminism sidebar|history}}
'''Fourth-wave feminism''' is a [[feminist movement]] that began around the early 2010s and is characterized by a focus on the [[empowerment of women]],<ref name="Abrahams-Prospect"/> the use of internet tools,<ref>{{Cite web|last=Grady|first=Constance|date=2018-03-20|title=The waves of feminism, and why people keep fighting over them, explained|url=https://www.vox.com/2018/3/20/16955588/feminism-waves-explained-first-second-third-fourth|access-date=2020-06-27|website=Vox|language=en}}</ref> and [[intersectionality]].<ref name="PSA"/> The fourth wave seeks greater gender equality by focusing on gendered norms and the marginalization of women in society.

Fourth-wave feminism focuses on sexual abuse, sexual harassment, sexual violence, the objectification of women, and sexism in the workplace. [[Internet activism]] is a key feature of the fourth wave.<ref name="Shiva">{{Cite book |last1=Shiva|first1=Negar|last2=Kharazmi|first2=Zohreh Nosrat|title=The Fourth Wave of Feminism and the Lack of Social Realism in Cyberspace |oclc=1236110330}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last1=Diamond |first1=Jill |last2=Dye |first2=Michaelanee |last3=LaRose |first3=Daphne |last4=Bruckman |first4=Amy |date=2013 |title=Holdback!: the role of storytelling online in a social movement organization |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/262314400 |access-date=2023-03-07 |website=Research Gate}}</ref> Fourth-wave feminism broadens its focus to other groups, including the LGBTQ+ community and people of color, and advocates for their increased societal participation and power.<ref name="PSA" /> It also advocates for equal incomes regardless of sex and challenges traditional gender roles for men and women, which it believes are oppressive. The movement further argues against sexual assault, objectification, harassment and gender-based violence.<ref name="Phillips 930–943" />

Some have identified the movement as a reaction to [[post-feminism]], which argues that women and men have already reached equality. It also brought back some second wave-feminist ideas into discourse, with Martha Rampton writing that the movement criticises "sexual abuse, rape, violence against women, unequal pay, slut-shaming, the pressure on women to conform to a single and unrealistic body-type",<ref name="Pacific University-2015">{{Cite web |date=2015-10-25 |title=Four Waves of Feminism |url=https://www.pacificu.edu/magazine/four-waves-feminism |access-date=2023-05-25 |website=Pacific University |language=en}}</ref> and advocates for "gains in female representation in politics and business".

==History and definition==
{{Further|first-wave feminism|second-wave feminism|third-wave feminism}}

Some feminists argue that in the 1980s conservative figures like [[Margaret Thatcher]] and [[Ronald Reagan]] challenged gains feminists had made up to that point.<ref name="codigonuevo-2018">{{Cite web|url=https://www.codigonuevo.com/mileniales/cuarta-ola-feminista-llegado-debes|title=La cuarta ola feminista ha llegado y esto es lo que debes saber|date=2018-03-05|website=Código Nuevo|language=es|access-date=2019-04-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425111743/https://www.codigonuevo.com/mileniales/cuarta-ola-feminista-llegado-debes|archive-date=25 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> At the same time, feminists in North America, Latin America, and Europe had succeeded in some of their goals, including the creation of state-run institutions that explicitly promoted women's rights, or feminist involvement in government; however, these institutions also weakened feminist movements by letting the state take over implementation of feminist goals.<ref>{{Cite magazine|last=Vega Ugalde|first=Silvia|date=2013|title=Comentarios al Dossier: "Nuevas voces feministas en América Latina: ¿continuidades, rupturas, resistencias?"|url=https://biblat.unam.mx/pt/revista/iconos-revista-de-ciencias-sociales/articulo/comentarios-al-dossier-nuevas-voces-feministas-en-america-latina-continuidades-rupturas-resistencias|magazine=Iconos. Revista de Ciencias Sociales|language=en|issue=46|pages=103–109|doi=10.17141/iconos.46.2013.58|issn=1390-1249|access-date=26 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426135304/https://biblat.unam.mx/pt/revista/iconos-revista-de-ciencias-sociales/articulo/comentarios-al-dossier-nuevas-voces-feministas-en-america-latina-continuidades-rupturas-resistencias|archive-date=26 April 2019|url-status=live|doi-access=free}}</ref>

European and Latin American third-wave feminism began in the 1990s, as ''[[lipstick feminism]]'' and ''consumerist feminism'' started to come to an end and as feminist activists were rejecting [[queer theory]] espoused by American academics.<ref name="Urzaiz-2017">{{Cite web|url=https://smoda.elpais.com/moda/actualidad/ana-miguel-filosofia/|title=Ana de Miguel: "Considerar que dar las campanadas medio desnuda es un acto feminista es un error garrafal"|last=Urzaiz|first=Begoña Gómez|date=2017-12-21|website=S Moda EL PAÍS|language=es-ES|access-date=2019-04-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425121930/https://smoda.elpais.com/moda/actualidad/ana-miguel-filosofia/|archive-date=25 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Guilló Girard-2018">{{Cite thesis|last=Guilló Girard|first=Clara Inés|title=El sentido de ser víctima y la víctima como sentido: tecnologías de enunciación de la violencia de género|date=2018|degree=Doctorate|publisher=UNIVERSIDAD COMPLUTENSE DE MADRID|url=http://isonomia.uji.es/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/ZZ.-Actas-Seminario-Int.-violencia-genero-2018.pdf|language=es|access-date=25 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425181934/http://isonomia.uji.es/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/ZZ.-Actas-Seminario-Int.-violencia-genero-2018.pdf|archive-date=25 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="webdeveloper-2019">{{Cite web|url=http://mujerdecantabria.com/estudio-la-recuperacion-integral-las-mujeres-victimas-violencia-genero-cantabria/|title=Estudio sobre la recuperación integral de las mujeres víctimas de violencia de género en Cantabria|last=webdeveloper|website=Dirección General de Igualdad y Mujer|language=es-ES|access-date=2019-04-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425185954/http://mujerdecantabria.com/estudio-la-recuperacion-integral-las-mujeres-victimas-violencia-genero-cantabria/|archive-date=25 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Kamchatka-2019">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kamchatka.es/es/feminismo-estrategico|title=Somos la Cuarta Ola; el feminismo estratégico|website=Kamchatka|language=es|access-date=2019-04-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426092329/https://www.kamchatka.es/es/feminismo-estrategico|archive-date=26 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Cuaderno-2018">{{Cite web|url=https://elcuadernodigital.com/2018/10/29/entrevista-a-beatriz-gimeno/|title=Entrevista a Beatriz Gimeno|last=Cuaderno|first=El|date=2018-10-29|website=El Cuaderno|language=es-ES|access-date=2019-04-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426132426/https://elcuadernodigital.com/2018/10/29/entrevista-a-beatriz-gimeno/|archive-date=26 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Las Gafas Violetas-2019">{{Cite web|url=https://lasgafasvioletasrevista.com/2019/03/07/somos-la-cuarta-ola-feminista/|title=¿Qué significa que somos la Cuarta Ola feminista?|date=2019-03-07|website=Las Gafas Violetas|language=es|access-date=2019-04-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426135307/https://lasgafasvioletasrevista.com/2019/03/07/somos-la-cuarta-ola-feminista/|archive-date=26 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Fourth-wave feminism developed slowly, globally via the media and the Internet.<ref name="Digital-2019">{{Cite web|url=https://www.estrelladigital.es/blog/tasia-aranguez-sanchez/cuarta-ola-movimiento-feminista/20181023183446356371.html|title=La cuarta ola del movimiento feminista|last=Digital|first=Estrella|website=Estrella Digital|language=es-ES|access-date=2019-04-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425111746/https://www.estrelladigital.es/blog/tasia-aranguez-sanchez/cuarta-ola-movimiento-feminista/20181023183446356371.html|archive-date=25 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Las Gafas Violetas-2019" /> The wave emerged from a new generation of women who had largely not been informed about previous waves through their education at high school, institutions and university. Knowledge about feminism was gained informally and it developed a virtual academy where feminists learned that "the personal is political"; it did not emerge from structured feminist learning.<ref name="Digital-2019" /> Fourth-wave feminism, like other waves before it, in this period was not about the existence of a single ideology, entity, or collective.<ref name="elperiodicodearagon">{{Cite web|url=https://www.elperiodicodearagon.com/noticias/aragon/pepa-bueno-estamos-cuarta-ola-imparable-feminismo_1321386.html|title=Pepa Bueno: 'Estamos en una cuarta ola imparable de feminismo'|last=Aragón|first=El Periódico de|website=El Periódico de Aragón|date=5 November 2018|language=es|access-date=2019-04-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425121929/https://www.elperiodicodearagon.com/noticias/aragon/pepa-bueno-estamos-cuarta-ola-imparable-feminismo_1321386.html|archive-date=25 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> It was about drawing together in collective groups to work together towards a common goal of ending violence against women in order to free them for the options to take the paths they desire; it was about mutual commitment and support to other women.<ref name="Lanza Digital-2019">{{Cite web|url=https://www.lanzadigital.com/provincia/manzanares/yolanda-besteiro-defiende-un-8-m-que-se-sienta-en-cada-uno-de-los-rincones-del-planeta-tambien-en-los-pueblos/|title=Yolanda Besteiro defiende un 8-M que se sienta "en cada uno de los rincones del planeta", también en los pueblos|date=2019-03-09|website=Lanza Digital|language=es-ES|access-date=2019-04-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426084505/https://www.lanzadigital.com/provincia/manzanares/yolanda-besteiro-defiende-un-8-m-que-se-sienta-en-cada-uno-de-los-rincones-del-planeta-tambien-en-los-pueblos/|archive-date=26 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

[[File:International Women's Day 2017 - 03 (33202921961).jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|[[International Women's Day]], London, 2017]]

The movement in Spain traces its roots to the [[murder of Ana Orantes]]; on 17 December 1997,<ref name="elperiodicodearagon" /><ref name="Urzaiz-2017" /> she was burned to death by her husband in her house in [[Granada]] for speaking publicly on {{lang|es|[[Canal Sur]]}} about how he abused her.<ref name="Albalat-2018">{{Cite web|url=https://www.elperiodico.com/es/sociedad/20181106/sentencia-navarra-la-manada-7132000|title=Juicio a 'la Manada', segunda parte|last=Albalat|first=Miriam Ruiz Castro / J. G.|date=2018-11-06|website=elperiodico|language=es|access-date=2019-04-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425181207/https://www.elperiodico.com/es/sociedad/20181106/sentencia-navarra-la-manada-7132000|archive-date=25 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="cuartopoder-2019">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cuartopoder.es/espana/2019/01/09/todo-lo-que-la-ley-contra-la-violencia-de-genero-ha-ensenado-a-la-generacion-8m/|title=Lo que Vox no te cuenta sobre la Ley contra la violencia de género|date=2019-01-09|website=Cuartopoder|language=es|access-date=2019-04-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425190005/https://www.cuartopoder.es/espana/2019/01/09/todo-lo-que-la-ley-contra-la-violencia-de-genero-ha-ensenado-a-la-generacion-8m/|archive-date=25 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Early fourth-wave Spanish feminism used television and newspapers as the primary social network.<ref name="elperiodicodearagon" /><ref name="Urzaiz-2017" /> Orantes' death brought domestic violence against women to national attention,<ref name="ConcienciaCultural-2019">{{Cite web|url=http://www.concienciacultural.com/nuria-coronado-periodista-y-activista-de-genero-sin-feminismo-no-hay-democracia/|title=Nuria Coronado, periodista y activista de género: "Sin feminismo, no hay democracia" {{!}} Conciencia Cultural|last=ConcienciaCultural|language=es|access-date=2019-04-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425121933/http://www.concienciacultural.com/nuria-coronado-periodista-y-activista-de-genero-sin-feminismo-no-hay-democracia/|archive-date=25 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Qué Leer-2019">{{Cite web|url=http://www.que-leer.com/2019/03/08/libros-sobre-feminismo/|title=FEMINISMO AL PODER|date=2019-03-08|website=Qué Leer|language=es|access-date=2019-04-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425121929/http://www.que-leer.com/2019/03/08/libros-sobre-feminismo/|archive-date=25 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and resulted in [[RTVE]] changing its policies on how the station reported on gender-based violence. Similar conversations took place at other television networks and media organizations across the country.<ref name="elperiodicodearagon" /> Jokes about domestic violence were no longer accepted on Spanish TV.<ref name="ConcienciaCultural-2019" /><ref name="cuartopoder-2019" /> Journalists from ''{{lang|es|[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]}}'', ''{{lang|es|[[El País]]}}'' and ''{{lang|es-419|[[infoLibre]]}}'' were among Spain's first participants in the fourth-wave, using their positions in the media to talk about a number of issues, mostly centered around sexist violence and its portrayal in the media. They later went on to talk about Spain's gender parity pay problems and promoted taking activism to virtual spaces.<ref name="Matiushkov Badia-2018">{{Cite book|url=https://ddd.uab.cat/record/199398|title=Las narrativas de Twitter sobre violencia machista|last1=Matiushkov Badia|first1=Tatiana|last2=Martínez García|first2=Luisa del Carmen|date=2018|others=Universitat Autònoma de Barcelona|access-date=25 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425174235/https://ddd.uab.cat/record/199398/|archive-date=25 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

The beginnings of this movement in this period took place in Latin America and Poland.<ref name="Arruzza-2019">{{Cite web|title=Cinzia Arruzza: "Las mujeres son las que están enfrentando el ascenso de la extrema derecha en todo el mundo"|url=https://www.infobae.com/america/eeuu/2018/12/09/cinzia-arruza-las-mujeres-son-las-que-estan-enfrentando-el-ascenso-de-la-extrema-derecha-en-todo-el-mundo/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426101920/https://www.infobae.com/america/eeuu/2018/12/09/cinzia-arruza-las-mujeres-son-las-que-estan-enfrentando-el-ascenso-de-la-extrema-derecha-en-todo-el-mundo/|archive-date=26 April 2019|access-date=2019-04-26|website=Infobae|date=9 December 2018 |language=es-ES}}</ref> Some of this global desire to act, particularly in a Polish context, came out of the [[World Conference on Women, 1995]] in [[Beijing]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nowaorgiamysli.pl/index.php/2018/02/12/czwarta-fala-feminizmu/|title=Czwarta Fala Feminizmu|date=2018-02-12|website=Nowa Orgia Myśli|language=pl-PL|access-date=2019-04-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190322115751/http://nowaorgiamysli.pl/index.php/2018/02/12/czwarta-fala-feminizmu/|archive-date=22 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

Social media had an amplifying effect as the fourth-wave feminist movement began to grow.<ref name="Albalat-2018" /><ref name="Hidalgo-2018">{{Cite web|url=https://www.elperiodico.com/es/extra/20181106/cuarta-ola-feminismo-motivos-movimiento-twitter-7130787|title=Las feministas reivindican la Cuarta Ola del movimiento y estos son sus motivos|last=Hidalgo|first=Mamen|date=2018-11-06|website=elperiodico|language=es|access-date=2019-04-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426135306/https://www.elperiodico.com/es/extra/20181106/cuarta-ola-feminismo-motivos-movimiento-twitter-7130787|archive-date=26 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Fourth-wave feminism began its peak in Spain, Argentina, [[2018 Chilean feminist protests and strikes|Chile]] and Brazil in 2018 as a result of a number of different factors, with women mobilized on a large scale to take to the streets.<ref name="cuartopoder-2019" /><ref name="abc-2018">{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.es/familia/mujeres/abci-40-anos-igualdad-constitucion-creimos-seriamos-iguales-pero-no-valia-solo-201812060213_noticia.html|title=40 años de igualdad en la Constitución: "Nos creímos que seríamos iguales, pero no valía solo con eso"|date=2018-12-06|website=abc|language=es|access-date=2019-04-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426063542/https://www.abc.es/familia/mujeres/abci-40-anos-igualdad-constitucion-creimos-seriamos-iguales-pero-no-valia-solo-201812060213_noticia.html|archive-date=26 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Hidalgo-2018" /> Their mobilization also challenged for the first time, the legitimacy of Spain's judiciary, whereas in previous waves the focus had been more on political leadership and acts of the legislature.<ref name="abc-2018" /> The wave in Spain would also face a major challenge, including the emergence of [[Vox (political party)|Vox]], a far right political party who won seats in [[Andalusia]]. Vox was opposed to The Organic Law of Comprehensive Protection Measures against Gender Violence and wanted to see it overturned.<ref name="cuartopoder-2019" />  In Argentina, the peak would be around the [[abortion rights]] issue which saw thousands of women with [[green scarves]] take to the streets.<ref name="Hidalgo-2018" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.clarin.com/entremujeres/genero/feminismo-aborto-cuarta-ola-feminista-victoria-freire_0_IGVMxGhBD.html|title=La cuarta ola feminista: mujeres al poder, pañuelos verdes y la lucha por el fin del patriarcado|last=Clarín.com|website=www.clarin.com|date=22 November 2018|language=es|access-date=2019-04-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181122173439/https://www.clarin.com/entremujeres/genero/feminismo-aborto-cuarta-ola-feminista-victoria-freire_0_IGVMxGhBD.html|archive-date=22 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>

In an [[Anglosphere]] feminist context, journalist Pythia Peay argued for the existence of a fourth wave as early as 2005, to focus on [[social justice]] and civil rights,<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Peay|first=Pythia|title=Feminism's Fourth Wave|magazine=[[Utne Reader]]|issue=128|year=2005|pages=59–60|url=http://www.utne.com/community/feminisms-fourth-wave.aspx|location=Topeka, Kansas|publisher=Ogden Publications|access-date=7 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160908222300/http://www.utne.com/community/feminisms-fourth-wave.aspx|archive-date=8 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> and in 2011, [[Jennifer Baumgardner]] dated the start of the fourth wave to 2008.{{sfn|Baumgardner|2011|p=250}} [[Twitter]], the social network most popular with the 18-to-29 age group, was created in 2006,<ref>{{Cite web |title=Twitter {{!}} History, Description, Elon Musk, & Uses {{!}} Britannica |url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Twitter |access-date=2022-11-21 |website=www.britannica.com |language=en}}</ref> making feminism more accessible and giving rise to "hashtag feminism".{{sfn|Bennett|2014}}

In 2013, Democratic Texas State Senator [[Wendy Davis (politician)|Wendy Davis]] staged a 13-hour [[Filibuster in the United States Senate|filibuster]] in Texas, in an attempt to prevent an anti-abortion bill from passing. Other women showed support by rallying around the [[Texas State Capitol]] and those who were not physically present used the [[hashtag]] #StandWithWendy. Similarly, women protested the perceived sexist questions (for example, focusing on appearance or love life) often directed at female celebrities by tweeting the hashtag #askhermore.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Chittal|first=Nisha|url=https://www.msnbc.com/msnbc/how-social-media-changing-the-feminist-movement|title=How Social Media is Changing the Feminist Movement|website=MSNBC|date=26 March 2015|access-date=21 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160419094625/http://www.msnbc.com/msnbc/how-social-media-changing-the-feminist-movement|archive-date=19 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>

Other feminist movements and "calls to action" have arisen from the fourth wave. One is the "HeForShe" campaign which originated from [[Emma Watson]]'s viral UN Women speech in 2014 and her subsequent activism.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hopkins|first=Susan|date=April 2018|title=UN celebrity 'It' girls as public relations-ised humanitarianism|journal=International Communication Gazette|volume=80|issue=3|pages=273–292|doi=10.1177/1748048517727223|s2cid=149182313|issn=1748-0485}}</ref> Several other incidents have galvanized the movement, including the [[Delhi gang rape]] (India, 2012), [[Jimmy Savile sexual abuse scandal|Jimmy Savile allegations]] (UK, 2012), [[Bill Cosby sexual assault cases]] (US, 2014), [[2014 Isla Vista killings|Isla Vista killings]] (US, 2014), [[trial of Jian Ghomeshi]] (Canada, 2016), [[Harvey Weinstein sexual abuse allegations|Harvey Weinstein allegations]] (US, 2017) and subsequent [[Me Too movement]] and [[Weinstein effect]], the [[2017 Westminster sexual scandals|Westminster sexual scandals]] (worldwide and UK, 2017) and the [[La Manada sexual abuse case|La Manada gang rape case]] in Spain (2018).<ref name="Cosboy-Ghomeshi-MeToo">For Cosby, Ghomeshi, #MeToo and fourth wave, see Matheson, Kelsey (17 October 2017). [http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/kelsey-matheson/you-said-metoo-now-what-are-we-going-to-do-about-it_a_23246129 "You Said #MeToo. Now What Are We Going To Do About It?"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171117065436/http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/kelsey-matheson/you-said-metoo-now-what-are-we-going-to-do-about-it_a_23246129/ |date=17 November 2017 }}, ''The Huffington Post''.</ref><ref>
For Savile and fourth wave, see {{harvnb|Chamberlain|2017|pp=114–15}}{{pb}}
For Isla Vista killings, see {{cite news|url=https://time.com/3319081/whyistayed-hashtag-feminism-activism/|title=Behold the Power of #Hashtag Feminism|last=Bennett|first=Jessica|date=10 September 2014|magazine=Time|access-date=21 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423085856/http://time.com/3319081/whyistayed-hashtag-feminism-activism/|archive-date=23 April 2016|url-status=live}}
</ref>

Due to the simultaneous existence of multiple waves of feminism – namely the second, third and fourth – many scholars are questioning the use of the wave metaphor in feminism. However, it is still the terminology most commonly used and most easily understood by the public. As the fourth wave finds much of its definition in relation to the previous ones, it is important to understand what the [[History of feminism|other waves]] were.<ref name="Evans-Critical-Waves">{{Cite journal|last1=Evans|first1=Elizabeth|last2=Chamberlain|first2=Prudence|date=July 2015|title=Critical Waves: Exploring Feminist Identity, Discourse and Praxis in Western Feminism|url=https://research-information.bristol.ac.uk/files/50807653/critical_waves_final_revisions.pdf|journal=Social Movement Studies|volume=14|issue=4|pages=396–409|doi=10.1080/14742837.2014.964199|hdl-access=free|hdl=1983/2b137a20-4d1e-41f6-b427-86046c1a32aa|s2cid=145460318}}</ref>

Internationally, comparisons between waves can be difficult. Anglospheric first-wave feminism is second-wave for Europeans and Latin American feminists. Second-wave American and British feminism is also third-wave for Europeans and Latin Americans.<ref name="Oliva Portolés-2019">{{Cite web|url=https://www.homonosapiens.es/podemos-hablar-de-una-cuarta-ola-en-el-movimiento-feminista-monografico-8m/|title=¿Podemos hablar de una cuarta ola en el movimiento feminista?|last=Oliva Portolés|first=Asunción|date=15 March 2019|website=Homonosapiens|language=es|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425120245/https://www.homonosapiens.es/podemos-hablar-de-una-cuarta-ola-en-el-movimiento-feminista-monografico-8m/|archive-date=25 April 2019|url-status=live|access-date=2019-04-25}}</ref> Spanish feminism went through several waves in the [[Franco era]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Spain - Franco's Spain, 1939–75 {{!}} Britannica |url=https://www.britannica.com/place/Spain/Francos-Spain-1939-75 |access-date=2022-11-21 |website=www.britannica.com |language=en}}</ref>

Broadly speaking, there are first-wave feminism taking place from the mid-nineteenth century to 1965, second-wave feminism taking place from 1965 to 1975 and third-wave feminism taking place from 1975 to 2012.<ref name="Díez Balda-2019">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mujeresenred.net/spip.php?article447|title=El Movimiento feminista en Salamanca después de la muerte de Franco|last=Díez Balda|first=Mª Antonia|website=mujeres en red|publisher=Universidad de Salamanca|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330085239/http://www.mujeresenred.net/spip.php?article447|archive-date=30 March 2019|url-status=live|access-date=2019-03-29}}</ref><ref name="Nielfa Cristóbal">Nielfa Cristóbal, Gloria. ''Movimientos femeninos'', en ''Enciclopedia Madrid S.XX''</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iisj.net/en/workshops/fourth-wave-feminism-sisterhood-and-social-networking-towards-new-citizenship|title=The fourth wave of feminism: from sisterhood and social networking towards a new citizenship?|date=2018-01-24|website=Instituto Internacional de Sociología Jurídica de Oñati|language=en|access-date=2019-03-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329102930/http://www.iisj.net/en/workshops/fourth-wave-feminism-sisterhood-and-social-networking-towards-new-citizenship|archive-date=29 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>  Fourth-wave feminism in Spain began in the mid-1990s.<ref name="elperiodicodearagon" /><ref name="Urzaiz-2017" /> When resolving waves around the work of important Spanish-speaking feminists discussing wave theory like [[Amelia Valcárcel]], the Spanish fourth-wave may at times actually represent an international fifth wave, not a fourth one.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Manzano Zambruno|first=Laura|date=2018|title=Apropiación ideológica y feminismo mediático: una aproximación crítica al caso Weinstein y el #MeToo en las ediciones digitales de S Moda y Mujerhoy|journal=Masters Thesis at Universidad de Sevilla, Departamento de Periodismo II|language=es|hdl=11441/78897}}</ref>

Each feminist wave has a separate identity, although they get harder to distinguish and define clearly as time goes on, due to debate among activists and scholars. In an Anglospheric feminist context, the [[First-wave feminism|first wave]] was characterized by the [[suffragette movement]]s and had the aim of legalizing women voting in public elections.<ref name="Evans-Critical-Waves" /> In the same context, [[Second-wave feminism|second wave]] is more difficult to comprehensively define, but is thought to have roots in the 1960s. Its focus shifted to social and personal rights, such as [[Equal pay for equal work|equal pay]], choice over bodily issues, [[sexual liberation]] and resistance to the gendered [[double standard]] in society.<ref name="Evans-Critical-Waves" /> There is much debate among Anglosphere academics and activists regarding the true definition of the [[Third-wave feminism|third wave]] of feminism. It is most commonly understood as a push by younger generations to create a feminism more centered on inclusivity; privileging the plights of [[queer]] and non-white women in their messaging. American poet [[Natasha Sajé]] has written, "[It] is an amalgamation of many different streams of theorizing—including that of women of color and younger women disillusioned with what they perceive to make up the body of 'second wave' feminism—in intrinsically different formulations than the theorizing coming from anti-feminists".<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Sajé|first1=Natasha|last2=Saje|first2=Natasha|date=1995|title=Then What Is the Question?|journal=Feminist Studies|volume=21|issue=1|pages=99|doi=10.2307/3178319|issn=0046-3663|jstor=3178319}}</ref><ref name="Evans-Critical-Waves" />

==Ideas==
British journalist [[Kira Cochrane]] and British feminist scholar Prudence Bussey-Chamberlain describe the fourth wave as focusing on justice for women, particularly opposition to [[sexual harassment]] (including street harassment), [[violence against women]], workplace discrimination and harassment, [[body shaming]], sexist imagery in the media, online misogyny, [[campus sexual assault]] and assault on public transport and [[rape culture]]. They also say it supports [[intersectionality]], social media activism and [[online petition]]ing.<ref name="4thWave-Guardian20131210">{{cite news|last=Cochrane|first=Kira|author-link=Kira Cochrane|date=10 December 2013|title=The Fourth Wave of Feminism: Meet the Rebel Women|newspaper=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/dec/10/fourth-wave-feminism-rebel-women|url-status=live|access-date=14 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314123922/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/dec/10/fourth-wave-feminism-rebel-women|archive-date=14 March 2016}}</ref><ref name="Abrahams-Prospect">{{cite news|last1=Abrahams|first1=Jessica|title=Everything you wanted to know about fourth wave feminism—but were afraid to ask|url=https://www.prospectmagazine.co.uk/magazine/everything-wanted-know-fourth-wave-feminism|work=Prospect|date=14 August 2017|access-date=17 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171117132924/https://www.prospectmagazine.co.uk/magazine/everything-wanted-know-fourth-wave-feminism|archive-date=17 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bcrw.barnard.edu/wp-content/nfs/reports/NFS8-FemFuture-Online-Revolution-Report-April-15-2013.pdf|title=#FemFuture: Online Revolution|last1=Martin|first1=Courtney E.|last2=Valenti|first2=Vanessa|publisher=Barnard Centre for Research on Women|date=15 April 2013|access-date=8 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160526211852/http://bcrw.barnard.edu/wp-content/nfs/reports/NFS8-FemFuture-Online-Revolution-Report-April-15-2013.pdf|archive-date=26 May 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Its essence, Chamberlain writes, is "incredulity that certain attitudes can still exist".{{sfn|Chamberlain|2017|p=115}} Events and organizations involved in fourth-wave feminism include [[Everyday Sexism Project]], [[Kat Banyard|UK Feminista]], [[Reclaim the Night]], [[One Billion Rising]] and "a Lose the Lads' mags protest".<ref name="4thWave-Guardian20131210" />

Books associated with the fourth wave include:
* ''[[Men Explain Things to Me]]'' (2014) by American writer [[Rebecca Solnit]] (notably, a 2008 essay also called ''Men Explain Things to Me,'' reprinted in the book, gave rise to the term ''[[mansplaining]]'')
* ''[[The Vagenda]]'' (2014) by British writers Rhiannon Lucy Cosslett and Holly Baxter (based on their online UJ feminist magazine, ''[[The Vagenda]]'', launched in 2012)
* ''Sex Object: A Memoir'' (2016) by American writer [[Jessica Valenti]]
* ''Everyday Sexism'' (2016) by British writer [[Laura Bates]] (based on Bates' [[Everyday Sexism Project]]){{sfn|Bates|2014}}

Cosslett and Baxter's book aims to debunk stereotypes of femininity promoted by mainstream women's press.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vagendamagazine.com/about|title=Letter from the Editor|publisher=The Vagenda|date=19 January 2012|access-date=3 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160527012815/http://vagendamagazine.com/about/|archive-date=27 May 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Bates, a British feminist writer, created the Everyday Sexism Project on 16 April 2012 as an online forum where women could post their experiences of everyday harassment.<ref name="Aitkenhead24Jan2016">{{cite news|last=Aitkenhead|first=Decca|author-link=Decca Aitkenhead|title=Laura Bates Interview: 'Two Years Ago, I Didn't Know What Feminism Meant'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jan/24/laura-bates-interview-everyday-sexism|newspaper=The Guardian|date=24 January 2014|access-date=14 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170207012945/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jan/24/laura-bates-interview-everyday-sexism|archive-date=7 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>

Third-wave feminists began introducing the concept of [[male privilege]] in their writings in the 1990s and fourth-wave feminists continue to discuss it in academia and on social media.<ref name="van der Gaag-2014">{{Cite book|title=Feminism and Men|last=van der Gaag|first=Nikki|date=2014|publisher=Zed Books|isbn=9781780329130|location=London|oclc=886112252}}</ref> American [[Peggy McIntosh]] was one of the first feminists to describe the phenomenon of privilege in 1988, calling it (in regards to white privilege) "an invisible weightless knapsack of special provisions, maps, passports, codebooks, visas, clothes, tools and blank checks."<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://files.eric.ed.gov/fulltext/ED355141.pdf?utm#page=43|title=White Privilege: Unpacking the Invisible Knapsack|last=Mcintosh|first=Peggy|date=July 1989|work=Peace and Freedom Magazine|access-date=March 20, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402042758/https://files.eric.ed.gov/fulltext/ED355141.pdf?utm#page=43|archive-date=2 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Fourth-wave feminists have taken action to reduce and combat this "knapsack" by raising awareness of privileged and unprivileged groups. [[Straight ally|Alliance]] is greatly encouraged by these feminists, who believe that males and other privileged groups can still take action for social change within their communities.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Systems of privilege: intersections, awareness, and applications|last=Case|first=Kim A.|date=2012|publisher=Wiley-Blackwell|oclc=799010636}}</ref>

London author Nikki van der Gaag discusses the damaging effects of raising young boys with privilege, citing the Consultative Group on Early Child Care and Development, "a tendency to privilege boys [...] does not teach teach boys responsibility, nor clarify what will be expected from them".<ref name="van der Gaag-2014" /> Fourth-wave feminists have begun promoting solutions to avoid these issues, such as raising children as [[gender-neutral]]. Professor of Neuroscience at Chicago Medical School [[Lise Eliot]] points out that infants and growing children are so impressionable that any small differences in raising the child can lead to large personality differences over time, resulting in reinforced gender stereotypes.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Pink brain, blue brain: how small differences grow into troublesome gaps—and what we can do about it|last=Eliot|first=Lise|date=2010|publisher=Mariner Books|isbn=9780547391557|location=Boston|oclc=837684360}}</ref>

Fourth-wave feminists have argued that reinforced [[Gender role|gender stereotypes]] create pressure for men to be breadwinners, as opposed to women, who feel obligated to take on the role of homemakers. Feminists argue that these pressures to conform socially can cause [[gender discrimination]] in the workplace and more widely in society.<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Ganesh|first1=Sarlaksha|last2=Ganesh|first2=Mangadu Paramasivam|date=2014-05-27|title=Effects of masculinity–femininity on quality of work life|journal=Gender in Management|volume=29|issue=4|pages=229–253|doi=10.1108/gm-07-2013-0085|issn=1754-2413}}</ref> According to [[Pew Research]], a majority of women working in male-dominated workplaces believe that sexual harassment is a problem in their industry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2018/03/07/women-in-majority-male-workplaces-report-higher-rates-of-gender-discrimination/|title=Gender discrimination more common for women in mostly male workplaces|website=Pew Research Center|date=7 March 2018 |access-date=2019-04-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402031653/https://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2018/03/07/women-in-majority-male-workplaces-report-higher-rates-of-gender-discrimination/|archive-date=2 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

== Intersectionality ==
One of the main critiques of past waves of feminism has been the centrality and privileging of the voices of middle class white women in the movement. The concept of intersectionality originates in black feminism throughout the 20th century and the specific term's coinage is attributed to [[Kimberlé Crenshaw|Kimberle Williams Crenshaw]] in 1991. Intersectionality in a broad sense is defined as "the interactivity of social identity structures such as race, class and gender in fostering life experiences, especially experiences of privilege and oppression".<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Gopaldas |first=Ahir |date=2013 |title=Intersectionality 101 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/43305317 |journal=Journal of Public Policy & Marketing |volume=32 |pages=90–94 |doi=10.1509/jppm.12.044 |jstor=43305317 |s2cid=220318967 |via=JSTOR}}</ref> It addresses the complexities of how different systems of oppression interact and overlap and has expanded to become a topic in fields of study outside of gender studies and feminism as well,<ref name="Okolosie-2014">{{Cite journal |last=Okolosie |first=Lola |date=2014 |title=beyond 'talking' and 'owning' intersectionality |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/24571923 |journal=Feminist Review |volume=108 |issue=108 |pages=90–96 |doi=10.1057/fr.2014.14 |jstor=24571923 |s2cid=147259709 }}</ref> and its main goal as a tool within the feminist movement is to give a voice and power to those who have been pushed to the margins, namely women of color and queer people.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Bose |first=Christine |date=February 2012 |title=Intersectionality and Global Gender Inequality |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/23212241 |journal=Gender and Society |volume=26 |issue=1 |pages=67–72 |doi=10.1177/0891243211426722 |jstor=23212241 |s2cid=145233506}}</ref>

While it has been used widely in conjunction with feminism since the 1990s, the fourth wave of feminism gives the concept a new level of prominence in the movement as the voices of those with marginalized identities are more easily heard with the use of social media. Intersectionality is most closely associated with black feminism in the eyes of both the general public and the world of academia, as a community operating under the oppressive systems of both racism and sexism and as the term intersectionality first gained traction through the work of black feminists. Some would say that "black feminists are read as the embodiment of intersectionality". While the use of intersectionality as a lens through which to view feminist discourse and practice has helped the movement make leaps of progress in regards to bringing forward the voices and needs of oppressed identities, the close association with black women and feminists has given rise to critiques on both sides of the debate.<ref name="Okolosie-2014" />

In terms of defending black women's experiences of intersectionality, one phrase that has been used is "I live it", in reference to the fact that critics are often attempting to disprove life experiences of black women that they have not themselves experienced or have grounds to falsify. Additional critiques against intersectionality from the viewpoint of white, middle-class leaders of feminism include the supposed use of the term to attack these leaders and the essentializing of gender oppression alone as opposed to all systems of oppression. For example, on a 2013 episode of 'Women's Hour' about fourth wave feminism, a Radio 4 program in the UK, a white feminist leader named Caroline Criado-Perez said "a big part of the problem is the way certain women use intersectionality as a cloak to abuse prominent white feminists". This was said in response to a critique of racism within modern feminism made by Reni Eddo-Lodge, a black feminist. On the other side, while intersectionality gives voices to marginalized communities it also often puts the labor of explaining and educating others about the term on those living under oppression, especially black women.<ref name="Okolosie-2014" />

Although a large percentage of activists operating under fourth wave feminism define themselves as intersectional feminists, intersectionality lives mostly in the realm of academia at this point in time.<ref name="Okolosie-2014" />

British professor of marketing and consumer research Pauline Maclaran<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1080/0267257X.2015.1076497 | volume=31 | issue=15–16 | title=Feminism's fourth wave: a research agenda for marketing and consumer research | year=2015 | journal=Journal of Marketing Management | pages=1732–1738 | last1 = Maclaran | first1 = Pauline| s2cid=145666422 }}</ref> argues that although celebrities are at the forefront of fourth-wave feminism, ready access to information has enabled the movement to draw greater attention to economic inequalities faced by women than heretofore possible.<ref name="Maclaran-2015">{{Cite journal|last=Maclaran|first=Pauline|date=2015-10-13|title=Feminism's fourth wave: a research agenda for marketing and consumer research|journal=Journal of Marketing Management|volume=31|issue=15–16|pages=1732–1738|doi=10.1080/0267257X.2015.1076497|issn=0267-257X|s2cid=145666422}}</ref>

Regarded as more inclusive of the [[LGBTQIA+]] community,<ref name="Maclaran-2015" /> fourth-wave feminists such as Jacob Bucher of [[Baker University]]<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1080/0735648X.2014.949823 | volume=38 | issue=4 | title=Soliciting strain: examining both sides of street prostitution through General Strain Theory | year=2015 | journal=Journal of Crime and Justice | pages=435–453 | last1 = Bucher | first1 = Jacob | last2 = Manasse | first2 = Michelle | last3 = Milton | first3 = Jeffrey| s2cid=143606247 }}</ref> have protested stereotypes surrounding men's supposed uncontrolled sexual desire and objectification of women. He states that gay men specifically are stigmatized by such stereotypes because they lie outside of the typical standard for masculinity.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bucher|first=Jacob|date=2014|title='But He Can't Be Gay': The Relationship between Masculinity and Homophobia in Father–Son Relationships|journal=Journal of Men's Studies|volume=22|issue=3|pages=222–237|doi=10.3149/jms.2203.222|s2cid=145751325}}</ref>

Canadian art historian [[Ruth Phillips]] argues that fourth-wave feminism falls within the broader agenda of financial, political and environmental concerns and is recognized as a key factor in alleviating poverty, improving women's health and achieving economic growth.<ref name="Phillips 930–943">{{Cite journal|last1=Phillips|first1=Ruth|last2=Cree|first2=Viviene E.|date=21 February 2014|title=What does the 'Fourth Wave' Mean for Teaching Feminism in Twenty-First Century Social Work?|url=https://www.pure.ed.ac.uk/ws/files/15148557/Phillips_Cree_Fourth_Wave_for_Open_Access.pdf|journal=Social Work Education|volume=33|issue=7|pages=930–43|doi=10.1080/02615479.2014.885007|s2cid=144660611|issn=0261-5479|hdl=20.500.11820/a5072043-e5e5-4cf1-af19-2207db4e19f7|hdl-access=free}}</ref>

In Latin American fourth-wave feminism, a similar concept to intersectionality is that of ''transversality''.<ref name="Langlois-2020">{{Cite web|last=Langlois|first=Aude|date=February 10, 2020|others=Department of Gender Studies|title=#NiUnaMenos: countering hegemonies in Argentina|url=https://blogs.lse.ac.uk/gender/2020/02/10/niunamenos-countering-hegemonies-in-argentina/ |access-date=October 4, 2021|website=[[London School of Economics and Political Science]]}}</ref><ref name="Palmeiro-2018">{{Cite journal|last=Palmeiro|first=Cecilia|date=2018-10-02|title=The Latin American Green Tide: Desire and Feminist Transversality|journal=Journal of Latin American Cultural Studies|volume=27|issue=4|pages=561–564|doi=10.1080/13569325.2018.1561429|s2cid=193082592|issn=1356-9325}}</ref> It describes "a form of feminism that addresses a wide range of issues in an effort to represent the heterogeneity of society".<ref name="Langlois-2020" /> Examples include addressing colonialism or racism, economic topics and LGBTQ issues.<ref name="Hosseini-2020" /><ref name="Langlois-2020" />

== Globally ==
