=== MeToo movement ===
[[Image:EleNao (Porto Alegre, 2018-09-29) 52.jpg|thumb|Protester in [[Porto Alegre]], [[Brazil]], participating in the [[Ele Não movement]]]]

In 2017, the [[MeToo movement|MeToo Movement]] originated in the United States to empower victims of sexual abuse and harassment. Other countries began their own hashtags with a similar goal, even though reactions of local governments differed. Hashtags associated with the worldwide MeToo Movement include:
*# AndNow or NowWhat<ref name="Roy-2018">{{Cite web|url=https://quebec.huffingtonpost.ca/2018/01/14/apres-moiaussi-etmaintenant_a_23333272/|title=Après #MoiAussi, #EtMaintenant|date=2018-01-14|website=HuffPost Québec|language=fr|access-date=2019-03-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190325180313/https://quebec.huffingtonpost.ca/2018/01/14/apres-moiaussi-etmaintenant_a_23333272/|archive-date=25 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> in Canada
* {{langnf|cmn-Latn|#WoYeShi|italic=no|MeToo}}<ref name="Phillips-2018">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jan/09/china-women-break-silence-harassment-metoo-woyeshi|title=China's women break silence on harassment as #MeToo becomes #WoYeShi|last=Phillips|first=Tom|date=2018-01-09|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-03-25|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180109041631/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jan/09/china-women-break-silence-harassment-metoo-woyeshi|archive-date=9 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> in China
* {{langnf|fr|#BalanceTonPorc|italic=no|term1=DenounceYourPig |term2=ExposeYourPig'}}<ref name="Tarnopolsky-2017">{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/world/middleeast/la-fg-global-me-too-20171018-story.html|title=A global primal scream: #MeToo (#YoTambien #QuellaVoltaChe #גםאנחנו أنا_كمان#)|first1=Noga|last1=Tarnopolsky|first2=Melissa|last2=Etehad|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=October 18, 2017|access-date=2019-03-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190326005204/https://www.latimes.com/world/middleeast/la-fg-global-me-too-20171018-story.html|archive-date=26 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> in France
*# NotinMyName<ref name="The Wire-2019">{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/gender/metoo-campaign-brings-the-rise-of-fourth-wave-feminism-in-india|title=#MeToo Campaign Brings the Rise of 'Fourth-Wave' Feminism in India|website=The Wire|access-date=2019-03-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190325180311/https://thewire.in/gender/metoo-campaign-brings-the-rise-of-fourth-wave-feminism-in-india|archive-date=25 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> in India
* {{langnf|it|#QuellaVoltaChe|italic=no|The Time That}}<ref name="Powell-2017">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newsweek.com/how-metoo-has-spread-wildfire-around-world-749171|title=How #MeToo has spread like wildfire around the world|date=2017-12-15|work=Newsweek|first=Catherine|last=Powell|access-date=2019-03-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190325180310/https://www.newsweek.com/how-metoo-has-spread-wildfire-around-world-749171|archive-date=25 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> in Italy
*# BoycottAliZafar, #BoycottTeefainTrouble, #TeefaisTrouble in Pakistan
* {{langnf|fil|#BabaeAko|italic=no|I Am a Woman}}<ref>{{Cite magazine|url=https://time.com/5345552/duterte-philippines-sexism-sona-women/|title=How President Duterte Sparked an Uprising of Filipina Women|magazine=Time|access-date=2019-03-25|date=2019-07-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190325180311/http://time.com/5345552/duterte-philippines-sexism-sona-women/|archive-date=25 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> in the Philippines
* {{langnf|es|#YoTambien|italic=no|MeToo}}<ref name="Powell-2017" /> in Spain
* [[Murder of Uyinene Mrwetyana|#AmINext]]<ref>{{Cite magazine|last=Lyster|first=Rosa|date=12 September 2019|title=The Death of Uyinene Mrwetyana and the Rise of South Africa's "Am I Next?" Movement|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/the-death-of-uyinene-mrwetyana-and-the-rise-of-south-africas-aminext-movement|access-date=28 June 2020|magazine=The New Yorker}}</ref> in South Africa

As the importance of social media in "creating and sustaining feminist community"<ref name="Evans-Critical-Waves" /> is an increasingly popular idea, "diversity and creativity continue to characterize feminist activism" around the world in the 21st century.<ref name="Evans-Critical-Waves" /> Communities around the globe witnessed the reflections of "the current, Internet-based fourth wave" feminism and investigated the difference of it.<ref name="Phillips 930–943" /> Moreover, the increasing social power of fourth-wave feminist movements prioritize these issues for elected governments, encouraging them to engage with the "new and young feminisms" of the modern day.<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Dean|first1=Jonathan|last2=Aune|first2=Kristin|date=2015-07-04|title=Feminism Resurgent? Mapping Contemporary Feminist Activisms in Europe|journal=Social Movement Studies|volume=14|issue=4|pages=375–395|doi=10.1080/14742837.2015.1077112|s2cid=143104696|issn=1474-2837}}</ref>

For instance, in [[Canada]], after the #MeToo hashtag started trending in October 2017, hundreds of people began to credit fourth-wave feminists with the movement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/metoo-movement-in-canada|title=#MeToo Movement in Canada|website=The Canadian Encyclopedia|access-date=2019-04-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401174416/https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/metoo-movement-in-canada|archive-date=1 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Another hashtag, #AndNow, became popular in Canada due to the support of Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]]. #AndNow supported discussing the solution to sexual harassment or abuse in the workplace to help people fight for equity between all people.<ref name="Roy-2018" />

In [[India]], there have been several movements or protests with large numbers of women, which have changed the perspective of many in the nation regarding femininity.<ref name="The Wire-2019" /> These include the 2003 [[Blank Noise|Blank Noise Project]], the 2009 [[Pink Chaddi Campaign|Pink Chaddi]] (underwear) movement, the 2011 [[SlutWalk]] protest, the 2015 [[Pinjra Tod]] (Break the Cage) movement and the 2017 Bekhauf Azadi (Freedom without Fear) March. Indian social discourse started to focus on long-term and deep-rooted issues, such as gender inequality, sexual violence, child marriage, sex-selective abortions and dowry-related violence. Many believe it led to the questioning of women's freedoms, choices and desires in society.<ref name="The Wire-2019" /> The influence and power of the campaign made the government expand the legal definition of rape, introduced "harsher punishment for rapists, criminalizing stalking and voyeurism",<ref name="The Wire-2019" /> showed "a new kind of Indian femininity that was comfortable with her modernity and sexuality"<ref name="The Wire-2019" /> and demonstrates the rise of fourth-wave feminism in India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/stopthisshame-girlsatdhaba-whyloiter-and-more-womens-fight-against-sexual-harassment-didnt-start-with-metoo-105711|title=#StopThisShame, #GirlsAtDhaba, #WhyLoiter and more: women's fight against sexual harassment didn't start with #MeToo|last=Kurian|first=Alka|website=The Conversation|date=7 March 2019 |language=en|access-date=2019-04-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190421142926/http://theconversation.com/stopthisshame-girlsatdhaba-whyloiter-and-more-womens-fight-against-sexual-harassment-didnt-start-with-metoo-105711|archive-date=21 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

''[[Ni una menos]]'' (meaning "Not One Less") is a Latin American feminist movement originating in Argentina which aims to end violence against women. The movement has engaged in women's strikes, including the [[International Women's Strike]].<ref name="Hosseini-2020">{{Cite book|last1=Hosseini|first1=S. A. Hamed|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yGAPEAAAQBAJ|title=The Routledge Handbook of Transformative Global Studies|last2=Goodman|first2=James|last3=Motta|first3=Sara C.|last4=Gills|first4=Barry K.|date=2020-06-09|publisher=[[Routledge]]|isbn=978-0-429-89339-1|pages=460–469|language=en|chapter=Feminized Resistances in Latin America}}</ref><ref name="Branigan-2018">{{Cite news|last1=Branigan|first1=Claire|last2=Palmeiro|first2=Cecilia|date=March 8, 2018|title=Women Strike in Latin America and Beyond|work=[[North American Congress on Latin America]]|url=https://nacla.org/news/2018/03/08/women-strike-latin-america-and-beyond|access-date=October 4, 2021}}</ref> ''Ni una menos'' has been described as fourth wave feminism.<ref name="Palmeiro-2018" /><ref name="Branigan-2018" /><ref name="broadly">{{cite web|last=Young|first=Linda|date=December 11, 2017|title=A Women's Strike Organizer on Feminism for the 99 Percent|url=https://broadly.vice.com/amp/en_us/article/3kpk53/-womens-strike-organizer-cecilia-palmeiro-feminism-for-the-99-percent |access-date=October 4, 2021|publisher=Broadly. [[Vice Media]]}}</ref> According to Cecilia Palmeiro, a founding member of the Ni Una Menos collective, "By connecting perspectives such as [[indigenous feminism]] with black feminism, migrant feminism, queer feminism and popular feminism, we made alliances and enlightened the intersection of violences as well as featured possible strategies of resistance. That is why our movement has been described as a fourth wave of feminism or [[Feminism of the 99%|feminism of the 99 percent]]."<ref name="Branigan-2018" /><ref name="broadly" />

In [[Brazil]], on September 19, 2018, the {{langnf|pt|[[Ele Não movement]]|not him}}, also known as the protests against [[Jair Bolsonaro]], were [[Demonstration (political)|demonstrations]] led by women which took place in several regions of the country as well as the world. The main goal was to protest against [[Jair Bolsonaro 2018 presidential campaign|Bolsonaro's presidential campaign]] and his sexist declarations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://brasil.elpais.com/brasil/2018/09/29/politica/1538226863_062834.html|title=Mulheres lideram multidão contra Bolsonaro em São Paulo, Rio e Recife|date=September 30, 2018|publisher=El País|language=pt-BR}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://exame.abril.com.br/brasil/15-imagens-que-resumem-os-atos-a-favor-e-contra-jair-bolsonaro-pelo-brasil/|title=15 imagens que resumem os atos a favor e contra Jair Bolsonaro pelo Brasil|date=September 30, 2018|publisher=Exame|language=pt-BR|access-date=22 September 2019|archive-date=28 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328181410/https://exame.abril.com.br/brasil/15-imagens-que-resumem-os-atos-a-favor-e-contra-jair-bolsonaro-pelo-brasil/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title=Um protesto histórico, menos na tevê|url=http://piaui.folha.uol.com.br/um-protesto-historico-menos-na-teve/|journal=Revista Piauí|date=30 September 2018 |language=pt-BR}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|date=2018-09-30|title=Mulheres quebram o jejum das ruas no Brasil com manifestações contra Bolsonaro|url=https://brasil.elpais.com/brasil/2018/09/30/politica/1538270819_523141.html|journal=El País|language=pt-BR}}</ref> It was being used even among national and international celebrities. [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] was one of the international celebrities who took part in the movement. She posted in her [[Instagram]], where she has more than 12.1 million followers, a picture in which she appears with her mouth sealed by a tape with the saying "freedom". Above, it reads in Portuguese {{lang|pt|"Ele não vai nos desvalorizar, ele não vai nos calar, ele não vai nos oprimir"}} (He won't devalue us, he won't silence us, he won't oppress us).<ref>{{cite journal|last=Sousa|first=Silvana|date=28 September 2018|title=#EleNão: Madonna adere à campanha contra Bolsonaro e pede o fim do fascismo|url=https://www.correiobraziliense.com.br/app/noticia/politica/2018/09/28/interna_politica,708917/madonna-adere-a-campanha-elenao-e-pede-pelo-fim-do-fascismo.shtml|journal=Correio Brasiliense|language=pt}}</ref>

Because Latin American fourth-wave feminism encompasses simultaneously distinct movements, many of which are in tension with one another, some refer to Latin American 'feminisms' in the plural.<ref>{{Citation|last=Rivera Berruz|first=Stephanie|title=Latin American Feminism|date=2018|url=https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/win2018/entries/feminism-latin-america/|encyclopedia=The Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy|editor-last=Zalta|editor-first=Edward N.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190503202647/https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/win2018/entries/feminism-latin-america/|edition=Winter 2018|publisher=Metaphysics Research Lab, Stanford University|access-date=2019-05-03|archive-date=3 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> One of the more controversial branches emerged as a reaction to and rejection of queer feminism and of [[postmodern feminism]],<ref name="Kamchatka-2019" /><ref name="Igualdad">{{Cite web|last=Igualdad|date=22 October 2018|title=El sujeto político feminista en la 4ª ola|url=https://www.eldiario.es/tribunaabierta/sujeto-politico-feminista-ola_6_827727257.html|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426101920/https://www.eldiario.es/tribunaabierta/sujeto-politico-feminista-ola_6_827727257.html|archive-date=26 April 2019|access-date=2019-04-26|website=eldiario.es|language=es}}</ref><ref name="Arruzza-2019" /><ref name="Cuaderno-2018" /> and consists of [[TERF|trans-exclusionary activists]] who reject prominent feminist academics like [[Judith Butler]] and much of feminist theory and seek to create a new anti-LGBT feminist movement by redefining 'woman' as exclusively [[cisgender]] and non-intersex, seeking to reframe the queer feminist movement not as an inclusive but as a watering-down of feminism and erasure of females.<ref name="Kamchatka-2019" /><ref name="Igualdad" /><ref name="Arruzza-2019" /> Whereas [[Queer theory|queer feminism]] was inclusive by expanding binary and [[cisnormative]] concepts of gender, these Latin American feminists argue that Butler was attempting to erase the concept of womanhood and thereby women as political subjects,<ref name="Kamchatka-2019" /> and reject [[gender studies]], calling it a conspiracy to hide women in academia.<ref name="Kamchatka-2019" /> Defining identity through biology instead of gender and replacing postmodern concepts of femininity with gender-essentialism, they frame queer feminism as a conspiracy to hide 'male' aggressors (trans women) and oppress females.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Espluga|first=Eudald|date=2018-01-12|title=Un movimiento, muchos feminismos: mapa de ideas para orientarse en las trincheras|url=https://www.playgroundmag.net/lit/Feminismos-un-mapa_26183342.html|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426101924/https://www.playgroundmag.net/lit/Feminismos-un-mapa_26183342.html|archive-date=26 April 2019|access-date=2019-04-26|website=PlayGround|language=es}}</ref><ref name="Kamchatka-2019" /><ref name="Arruzza-2019" /><ref name="Cuaderno-2018" />

== Roe v. Wade overturn ==
On June 24, 2022, The U.S. Supreme Court ruled 6-3, in favor of [[Dobbs v. Jackson Women's Health Organization|Dobbs v. Jackson Women's Health Organization]] which subsequently overruled the previous landmark Supreme Court case of [[Roe v. Wade]] as well as [[Planned Parenthood v. Casey]]. ''Dobbs v. Jackson Women's Health Organization'' ruled that the Constitution of the United States does not confer the right to an abortion. The case was presented on the Constitutionality of a 2018 Mississippi law that banned abortion operations after the 15th week of pregnancy.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Littlefield |first=Amy |date=2021-11-30 |title=The Christian Legal Army Behind the Ban on Abortion in Mississippi |url=https://www.thenation.com/article/politics/alliance-defending-freedom-dobbs/ |access-date=2024-03-05 |language=en-US |issn=0027-8378}}</ref> This ruling makes ''Dobbs'' to be considered a landmark decision of the court. The decision on June 24, 2022 came after a leak on May 2, 2022, which showed leaked documents of the majority opinion by [[Samuel Alito|Justice Samuel Alito]], which criticized ''Roe''. The following day the Supreme Court confirmed these documents to be legitimate but stated these documents do "not represent a decision by the Court or the final position of any member on the issues in the case".<ref>United States Supreme Court. "Remote Oral Arguments to Continue for April Session of Court." Supreme Court of the United States, 3 May 2022, <nowiki>https://www.supremecourt.gov/publicinfo/press/pressreleases/pr_05-03-22</nowiki>.</ref>

The impact of the overturn of ''Roe v. Wade'' was significant and impactful for all women across the country. Once ''Roe'' was overturned, various states across the United States followed suit in determining their stance on the Constitutionality of a protected right to abortion. Some states' older restrictions on abortion that were put on hold after ''Roe'' was passed, were now put back into place. Many states also had [[trigger law]]s that were put into place in May 2021, when the Supreme Court agreed to hear ''Dobbs'' arguments.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Kelly |first=Caroline |date=2021-05-18 |title=More states are expected to pass anti-abortion bills targeting Roe v. Wade {{!}} CNN Politics |url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/05/18/politics/mississippi-abortion-case-impact-supreme-court-abortion-bans-activists/index.html |access-date=2024-03-05 |website=CNN |language=en}}</ref> These states include Arkansas, Idaho, Kentucky, Louisiana, Mississippi, Missouri, North Dakota, Oklahoma, South Dakota, Tennessee, Texas, Utah, and Wyoming. Some of the states never removed their pre-Roe abortion bans. They were unable to be enacted while ''Roe'' was in effect, but were put back into place after the overturning of ''Roe.''<ref>{{Cite web |last=Office 202 296-4012 |first=Public Policy |date=2016-03-14 |title=Abortion Policy in the Absence of Roe {{!}} Guttmacher Institute |url=https://www.guttmacher.org/state-policy/explore/abortion-policy-absence-roe |access-date=2024-03-05 |website=www.guttmacher.org |language=en}}</ref>

[[United States abortion protests (2022–present)|Protests]] spread all across the U.S. after the announcement of the overturn of ''Roe''. These protests were largely peaceful and were carried out in 46 states.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Noor |first=Poppy |date=2023-01-22 |title=Women's March draws thousands across US after Roe v Wade overturned |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/jan/22/womens-march-2023-roe-v-wade-abortion-rights |access-date=2024-03-05 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>

The medical impact of the overturn of ''Roe'' has large and significant implications for medical and nursing education "and will reshape the knowledge, skills, and quality of care provided by future physicians and nurses, particularly in states with bans on abortion or pregnancy age restrictions".<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Berg |first1=Judith A. |last2=Woods |first2=Nancy Fugate |date=2023-01-06 |title=Overturning Roe v. Wade: consequences for midlife women's health and well-being |journal=Women's Midlife Health |volume=9 |issue=1 |pages=2 |doi=10.1186/s40695-022-00085-8 |doi-access=free |issn=2054-2690 |pmc=9824972 |pmid=36609311}}</ref> Medical students without the knowledge to perform a safe and legitimate abortion will also not have the knowledge to treat other pregnancy related complications such as placental abruption, infections, ectopic pregnancy, and eclampsia, because the techniques and tools used during these procedures are similar or the same to a standard abortion.<ref>Dhillon, Rajveer Singh, et al. "The spread of misinformation and fake news: Impact on public health during a pandemic." The Lancet American Health, vol. 1, no. 2, 2022, pp. e82-e84. <nowiki>https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lanam/article/PIIS2667-193X(22)00151-X/fulltext</nowiki></ref> As abortion education within our country declines, the long-term quality of reproductive care in the United States will likely deteriorate. Studies showed that in comparison to women who had an abortion, those who were forced to carry an unintended pregnancy to term and give birth, had poorer physical health.<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal |url=https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jamapsychiatry/fullarticle/2592320 |access-date=2024-03-05 |journal=JAMA Psychiatry|doi=10.1001/jamapsychiatry.2016.3478 |title=Women's Mental Health and Well-being 5 Years After Receiving or Being Denied an Abortion |date=2017 |last1=Biggs |first1=M. Antonia |last2=Upadhyay |first2=Ushma D. |last3=McCulloch |first3=Charles E. |last4=Foster |first4=Diana G. |volume=74 |issue=2 |pages=169–178 |pmid=27973641 }}</ref> Similarly, women who were denied an abortion also had poorer well-being and reported an incline in their anxiety and depression as soon as a week after being denied.<ref name=":0" />

The discussion of where fourth-wave feminism falls into the overturning of ''Roe'' is on-going online.

==Social media==
While previous waves of feminism have encountered such obstacles as rigid sociopolitical structures and a lack of available communication channels,<ref name="Schuller-2018">{{Cite book|last=Schuller, Kyla|title=The Biopolitics of Feeling: Race, Sex, and Science in the Nineteenth Century|date=2018|publisher=Duke University Press|isbn=9780822372356|oclc=1050035724}}</ref> fourth-wave feminists harness [[digital media]] as a far-reaching platform on which to connect, share perspectives, create a broader view of experienced oppression and critique past feminist waves.<ref name="Baer-2016">{{Cite journal|last=Baer|first=Hester|date=2016-01-02|title=Redoing feminism: digital activism, body politics, and neoliberalism|journal=Feminist Media Studies|language=en|volume=16|issue=1|pages=17–34|doi=10.1080/14680777.2015.1093070|issn=1468-0777|s2cid=146135612}}</ref><ref name="Evans-Critical-Waves" /><ref name="4thWave-Guardian20131210"/> Some argue that the use of technology in fourth-wave feminism signified a shift out of post-feminism and out of exclusively scholarly discussions.<ref name="Shiva-2019">{{Cite journal |last1=Shiva |first1=Negar |last2=Nosrat Kharazmi |first2=Zohreh |date=July 2019 |title=The Fourth Wave of Feminism and the Lack of Social Realism in Cyberspace |url=https://doi.org/10.22059/jcss.2019.72456 |journal=Journal of Cyberspace Studies |volume=3 |issue=2 |doi=10.22059/jcss.2019.72456}}</ref> Social media allows women to share their experiences from all over the world and is a space where people can rally for change.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Zimmerman |first=Tegan |date=June 9, 2017 |title=#Intersectionality: The Fourth Wave Feminist Twitter Community |url=https://journals.msvu.ca/index.php/atlantis/article/view/4304/54-70%20PDF |journal=Atlantis: Critical Studies in Gender, Culture & Social Justice |volume=38 |issue=1 |pages=54–70}}</ref> It allows a broader range of people to participate in feminist discussions, debates and activism. In the past, these debates have often existed exclusively in the world of acedemia, leading to a smaller range of perspectives that have limited previous movements.<ref name="Crane-2012">{{Cite journal |last=Crane |first=Connie Jeske |date=Fall 2012 |title=Social Media as a Feminist Tool |url=https://0-search-ebscohost-com.librarycat.risd.edu/login.aspx?direct=true&db=aph&AN=82073633&site=ehost-live&scope=site |journal=Horizons |volume=26 |issue=2 |pages=14–16 |via=EBSCOhost}}</ref> Due to the global participation made possible by the internet, it has been argued that the fourth-wave exists online.<ref name="Shiva-2019"/>

[[Kira Cochrane]] has argued that fourth-wave feminism is "defined by technology" and characterized particularly by the use of [[Facebook]], [[Twitter]], [[Instagram]], [[YouTube]], [[Tumblr]] and blogs such as [[Feministing]] to challenge [[misogyny]].<ref name="4thWave-Guardian20131210" /><ref name="Solomon-2009">{{Cite news|last=Solomon|first=Deborah|date=13 November 2009|title=The Blogger and Author on the Life of Women Online|work=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/11/15/magazine/15fob-q4-t.html|url-status=live|access-date=16 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160716184154/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/11/15/magazine/15fob-q4-t.html|archive-date=16 July 2016}}</ref><ref name="Zerbisias-2016">{{Cite web|last=Zerbisias|first=Antonia|date=16 September 2015|title=Feminism's Fourth Wave is the Shitlist|url=https://nowtoronto.com/news/feminisms-fourth-wave-is-the-shitlist|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151016172423/https://nowtoronto.com/news/feminisms-fourth-wave-is-the-shitlist/|archive-date=16 October 2015|access-date=21 April 2016|website=NOW Toronto}}</ref>

The speed of communication and concept of "going viral" has been a major factor in the success of contemporary feminist campaigns, fostering digital phenomenon such as "call-out culture". In the world of cyberfeminism, call-out culture is used as a tool to accuse sexual predators in a manner that allows for optional anonymity and the larger possibility of wide-ranged support. Hashtag feminism campaigns are often a result of this culture.<ref name="Shiva-2019"/>

Social media activism has manifested as Twitter threads critiquing perceived [[transphobia]] in the media<ref>{{Citation|last=Parry|first=Diana C.|title=Feminisms in Leisure Studies|pages=1–12|year=2018|chapter=Fourth wave feminism|publisher=Routledge|doi=10.4324/9781315108476-1|isbn=9781315108476|s2cid=195569730}}</ref> and in so-called "hashtag feminism" campaigns, notably [[Me Too movement|#MeToo]],<ref name="Cosboy-Ghomeshi-MeToo" /> [[YesAllWomen|#YesAllWomen]], [[Chibok schoolgirls kidnapping|#bringbackourgirls]], #NotYourAsianSidekick and [[Black Twitter|#SolidarityIsForWhiteWomen]].<ref>{{Cite news |date=2013-08-14 |title=#SolidarityIsForWhiteWomen: women of color's issue with digital feminism |author=Mikki Kendall |url=http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/aug/14/solidarityisforwhitewomen-hashtag-feminism |access-date=2022-11-21 |newspaper=The Guardian |language=en}}</ref> Girlgaze, launched by [[Amanda de Cadenet]], is an online multi-sided platform that directly connects businesses, companies and brands with women and non-binary creative talent,<ref>{{Cite web|title=girlgaze.com|url=https://girlgaze.com |website=Girlgaze}}</ref> promoting the need for diversity, inclusion and representation across the creative industry. [[Time (magazine)|''Time'']] named a group of activists prominent in the #MeToo movement, dubbed "the silence breakers", as its 2017 [[Time Person of the Year|Person of the Year]].<ref name="Zacharek6Dec2017">Zacharek, Stephanie; Dockterman Eliana; and Sweetland Edwards, Haley (6 December 2017). [https://time.com/time-person-of-the-year-2017-silence-breakers/ "The Silence Breakers"] , ''Time'' magazine.</ref><ref>Redden, Molly, and agencies (6 December 2017). [https://www.theguardian.com/media/2017/dec/06/metoo-movement-named-time-magazines-person-of-the-year "#MeToo movement named Time magazine's Person of the Year"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171207033815/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2017/dec/06/metoo-movement-named-time-magazines-person-of-the-year|date=7 December 2017}}, ''The Guardian''.</ref><ref>For page three, see Thorpe, Vanessa (27 July 2013). [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/jul/27/new-generation-of-feminists-set-agenda "What now for Britain's new-wave feminists&nbsp;– after page 3 and £10 notes?"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171111041558/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/jul/27/new-generation-of-feminists-set-agenda|date=11 November 2017}}, ''The Guardian''.</ref>

Other fourth-wave feminist campaigns include the [[Feminist Coalition]], [[Everyday Sexism Project]], [[No More Page 3]], {{lang|es|[[Ni una menos]]}}, [[Stop Bild Sexism|Stop ''Bild'' Sexism]], [[Free the Nipple (campaign)|Free the Nipple]], [[SlutWalk]], the [[2017 Women's March|2017]] and [[2018 Women's March]]es, [[Time's Up (organization)|Time's Up]] and [[One Billion Rising]]. Artistic endeavors include ''[[Mattress Performance (Carry That Weight)|Mattress Performance]]'' and ''[[10 Hours of Walking in NYC as a Woman]]''.<ref>{{Citation |title=10 Hours of Walking in NYC as a Woman | date=28 October 2014 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=b1XGPvbWn0A |language=en |access-date=2022-11-21}}</ref>

The Everyday Sexism Project, established in 2012 by feminist author Laura Bates, is an example of a fourth-wave feminist campaign that began online and utilized the internet as a medium for women to share stories of sexism and sexual assault they had faced through the use of a hashtag and sites like Twitter and blogs. The project brought awareness to the prolific nature of structurally ingrained sexism and gendered violence that is often a stigmatized topic in the everyday.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Day and Wray |first=K and R |date=2018 |title=Fourth-wave feminism and postfeminism: Successes and failures |url=https://eprints.leedsbeckett.ac.uk/id/eprint/7735/1/FourthWaveFeminismAndPostfeminismSuccessesAndFailuresAM-WRAY.pdf |journal=Transform: A Journal of the Radical Left |volume=4 |pages=113–137 |via=Google Scholar}}</ref>

One critique of social media feminism is the emotional toll it can take on active leaders and participants as a form of unpaid labor that can often have harsh repercussions in the form of online harassment and abuse.<ref name="Shiva-2019"/><ref name="Crane-2012"/>

Sahar Khamis, a professor at University of Maryland, argues that social media gives feminists a unique avenue to highlight moments of solidarity in the social movement creating a powerful energy.<ref name="Oren-2019">{{cite book |last1=Oren |first1=Tasha |chapter=Contemporary feminism |doi=10.4324/9781315728346-1 |title=The Routledge Handbook of Contemporary Feminism |pages=1–19 |place=Abingdon, Oxon |publisher=Routledge |date=2019 |isbn=978-1-315-72834-6 |last2=Press |first2=Andrea L. |s2cid=216612655 |editor=Oren |editor2=Press}}</ref> Social media allows interconnected groups and individuals to network and connect with each other. Younger generations of feminists are more likely to form their beliefs and opinions and develop their support for the movement through social media.<ref name="Oren-2019" />

== Men and the fourth wave ==

=== Importance of men's participation ===
According to the International Women's Development Agency, feminism is "about all genders having equal rights and opportunities."<ref>{{Cite web |title=What Is Feminism? {{!}} IWDA |url=https://iwda.org.au/learn/what-is-feminism/ |access-date=2024-03-06 |language=en-AU}}</ref> More than 70% of U.S. fathers take parental leave, but receive less than two weeks off after the birth of their child.<ref name=":10">{{Cite web |last=Sutanto |first=Cynthia |date=2023-12-12 |title=Feminism is for Men, Too |url=https://feminist.org/news/feminism-is-for-men-too/ |access-date=2024-03-06 |website=Feminist Majority Foundation |language=en-US}}</ref> Four times more men than women die by suicide in the U.S., due to stigma around mental health and seeking help for it.<ref name=":10" />

In [[Emma Watson]]'s 2014 speech launching the [[HeForShe]] campaign for [[UN Women]], she points out that "men don't have the benefits of equality either."<ref name=":9">{{Cite web |date=2014-09-20 |title=Emma Watson: Gender equality is your issue too |url=https://www.unwomen.org/en/news/stories/2014/9/emma-watson-gender-equality-is-your-issue-too |access-date=2024-02-29 |website=UN Women – Headquarters |language=en}}</ref> She cites examples from her own life where she has noticed this, including seeing her "father's role as a parent being valued less by society," and witnessing her male friends struggle to express their emotions.<ref name=":9" /> From the HeForShe website, HeForShe is "an invitation for men and people of all genders to stand in solidarity with women" in order to achieve gender equality for everyone.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Home Page |url=https://www.heforshe.org/en |access-date=2024-02-29 |website=HeForShe |language=en}}</ref>

=== Challenges for male feminists ===
Societal pressure and the ideals of [[toxic masculinity]] can make it difficult for men to support [[feminism]].<ref name=":12">{{Cite web |last=Flood |first=Michael |date=2022-09-21 |title='Toxic masculinity': what does it mean, where did it come from – and is the term useful or harmful? |url=http://theconversation.com/toxic-masculinity-what-does-it-mean-where-did-it-come-from-and-is-the-term-useful-or-harmful-189298 |access-date=2024-02-27 |website=The Conversation |language=en-US}}</ref> In many societies, to be considered 'masculine', men must be "strong, active, aggressive, tough, daring, heterosexual, emotionally inexpressive and dominant."<ref name=":12" /> Among these types of traits is the idea present in many cultures globally that being a man "often involve[s] male domination over women."<ref name=":10" />

Fourth wave feminism has been able to reach a larger audience than the previous waves via social media.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-05-04 |title=The Social Media Revolution is Reshaping Feminism - National Organization for Women |url=https://now.org/blog/the-social-media-revolution-is-reshaping-feminism/ |access-date=2024-03-06 |website=now.org |language=en-US}}</ref> In May 2023, researchers conducted an experiment designed to find the effect of feminist content on social media on [[Millennials|millennial]] men and men from [[Generation Z]].<ref name=":02">{{Cite journal |last1=Kosar |first1=Sophia Anneliese |last2=Muruthi |first2=Bertranna A. |last3=Shivers |first3=Carolyn |last4=Zarate |first4=Jose |last5=Byron |first5=Jordan |date=October 2023 |title=Millennials and Generation Z: Men's Perspectives on Hashtag Feminism |url=http://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.1177/10608265231175832 |journal=The Journal of Men's Studies |language=en |volume=31 |issue=3 |pages=478–499 |doi=10.1177/10608265231175832 |hdl=10919/102110 |s2cid=258655810 |issn=1060-8265|hdl-access=free }}</ref> The findings included mixed messages, with one participant stating that so-called 'hashtag' feminism "[spread] real awareness of the struggles women face that [men] are not all the time aware of, and sometimes never aware of."<ref name=":02" /> The participants also felt that hashtag feminism was difficult for men to engage with, with one man stating that he doesn't "know how to engage with it in a way that doesn't come off as hostile."<ref name=":02" />

=== Men's feminist media and advocacy ===
In more recent years, the number of men acting to publicly support feminism has increased; celebrities such as [[Justin Baldoni]], [[Terry Crews]], [[Matt McGorry]], and [[Alan Cumming]] have spoken and acted in support of the movement.<ref name=":22">{{Cite web |date=2019-11-25 |title=Five Feminist Men We Are Thankful For |url=https://therepproject.org/five-feminist-men-we-are-thankful-for/ |access-date=2024-02-27 |website=The Representation Project |language=en-US}}</ref> Baldoni's TED Talk, "Why I'm done trying to be man enough", asks questions like "are you brave enough to be vulnerable?" and "are you strong enough to be sensitive?"<ref name=":32">{{Cite web |title=Why I'm done trying to be "man enough" - Justin Baldoni |url=https://ed.ted.com/lessons/83OhjZcY |access-date=2024-02-27 |website=TED-Ed |language=en}}</ref> "Why I'm done trying to be man enough" touches on recognizing privilege, amplifying women's voices, and the importance of creating male friendships in which men can speak about real struggles together.<ref name=":32" /> In 2014, Terry Crews published his book, ''Manhood: How to Be a Better Man–or Just Live with One'', a memoir discussing how to be a "good man, loving husband, and responsible father."<ref>{{Cite web |title=Manhood: How to Be a Better Man - or Just Live with One |url=https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/19287159-manhood |access-date=2024-02-27 |website=Goodreads |language=en}}</ref> Crews has also publicly voiced his support for gender equality in an interview with BUILD Series<ref>{{Citation |title=Terry Crews Speaks Out Against Toxic Masculinity | date=22 January 2020 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nhWZPopmIto |access-date=2024-02-27 |language=en}}</ref> and on his [[Twitter]] account.<ref name=":22" />

In addition to celebrities, former president [[Barack Obama]] authored an article titled "This is What a Feminist Looks Like", discussing gender roles and the need for everyone to fight [[sexism]].<ref name=":4">{{Cite web |last=Obama |first=Barack |date=2016-08-04 |title=Exclusive: President Barack Obama Says, "This Is What a Feminist Looks Like" |url=https://www.glamour.com/story/glamour-exclusive-president-barack-obama-says-this-is-what-a-feminist-looks-like |access-date=2024-02-27 |website=Glamour |language=en-US}}</ref> Obama asserts that gender stereotypes "limit our ability to simply be ourselves" and that twenty-first century feminism is "the idea that when everybody is equal, we are all more free."<ref name=":4" />

In September 2014, the Obama-Biden White House founded [[It's On Us|It's On Us]], which became the largest nonprofit dedicated to preventing sexual assault on college campuses in the U.S.<ref>{{Cite web |title=It's On Us {{!}} Our Story |url=https://itsonus.org/about-us/our-story/ |access-date=2024-02-27 |language=en-US}}</ref>

In 2015, ''[[The Mask You Live In]]'', a documentary film directed by [[Jennifer Siebel Newsom]], premiered at [[Sundance Film Festival]].<ref>{{Citation |last=Newsom |first=Jennifer Siebel |title=The Mask You Live In |date=2015-01-25 |type=Documentary, News |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3983674/ |access-date=2024-02-27 |others=Joe Herman, Michael Kimmel, Caroline Heldman |publisher=The Representation Project, The Annenberg Foundation, The Brin Wojcicki Foundation}}</ref> The documentary details the environment and expectations that boys grow up with in the United States, using analysis from experts in various fields and firsthand accounts of experiences to illustrate how gender roles affect boys and men.<ref>{{Cite web |title=THE MASK YOU LIVE IN |url=https://therepproject.org/films/the-mask-you-live-in/ |access-date=2024-02-27 |website=The Representation Project |language=en-US}}</ref>

In 2017, [[Alec Baldwin]], [[Michael Moore]], [[Ian McKellen]], [[Rufus Wainwright]], and [[John Legend]], along with a plethora of female public figures, attended women's marches across the country.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Park |first=Andrea |date=2017-01-23 |title=Celebrities attend Women's Marches around the world |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/pictures/celebrities-attend-womens-marches-around-the-world/ |access-date=2024-02-27 |website=www.cbsnews.com |language=en-US}}</ref>

