==Criticism==
One criticism of fourth-wave feminism is that it depends on digital and emerging technology, which means enabling underserved communities to engage with digital tools in a way that is empowering, these arguments are advanced and countered in the pioneering work of [[Nancy Mauro-Flude]], recognised for her integration of performance art, digital media, and critical technology studies, with a focus on feminist perspectives and the politics of digital literacy.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Mauro-Flude |first1=Nancy |title=Writing the Feminist Internet: a Chthonian Feminist Internet Theory for the twenty first century |journal=Continuum |date=15 Oct 2021 |volume=35 |issue=5 |pages=788–804 |doi=10.1080/10304312.2021.1983260 |url=https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/10304312.2021.1983260}}</ref> Using an image of [[Nancy Mauro-Flude]] theatre work Error_in_Time()<ref>{{cite web |last1=Grady |first1=Kendall |title=you will _KNOW how_ : interview with Nancy Mauro-Flude |url=https://mastersofmedia.hum.uva.nl/blog/2011/10/31/you-will-_know-how_-an-interview-with-nancy-mauro-flude/ |website=Masters of Media |date=31 October 2011 |access-date=October 31, 2011}}</ref> to start her article, Ragna Rök Jóns argued that "[t]he key problem that this '4th Wave' will face will be the disproportionate access to and ownership of digital media devices." The fourth wave is left with the "inherent [[classism]] and [[ableism]]" created by giving the greatest voice to those who can afford and use technology,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bluestockingsmag.com/2013/08/19/is-the-4th-wave-of-feminism-digital/|title=Is the '4th Wave' of Feminism Digital?|last=Jóns|first=Ragna Rök|website=Bluestockings Magazine|date=19 August 2013|access-date=21 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160220193323/http://bluestockingsmag.com/2013/08/19/is-the-4th-wave-of-feminism-digital/|archive-date=20 February 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> while the growth of social media in regions plagued by pervasive social injustice remains slow.<ref name="PSA">{{Cite journal|last=Munro|first=Ealasaid|date=September 2013|title=Feminism: A Fourth Wave?|journal=Political Insight|volume=4|issue=2|pages=22–25|doi=10.1111/2041-9066.12021|s2cid=142990260}} Republished as {{Cite web|last=Munro|first=Ealasaid|date=5 September 2013|title=Feminism: A fourth wave?|url=https://www.psa.ac.uk/insight-plus/feminism-fourth-wave|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181202070519/https://www.psa.ac.uk/insight-plus/feminism-fourth-wave|archive-date=2 December 2018|access-date=1 December 2018|website=The Political Studies Association}} / {{Cite web|title=Feminism: A fourth wave? {{!}} The Political Studies Association (PSA)|url=https://www.psa.ac.uk/psa/news/feminism-fourth-wave|access-date=2020-06-27|website=Feminism: A fourth wave? {{!}} The Political Studies Association (PSA)|language=en}}</ref> North American sociologist Amanda E. Vickery claims that fourth-wave feminism marginalizes women of color who are fighting for inclusivity, neglecting the specific injustices they face to make way for the mainstream struggle.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Vickery |first=Amanda Elizabeth |year=2018 |title=After the March, What? Rethinking How We Teach the Feminist Movement |journal=Social Studies Research & Practice |volume=13 |issue=3 |pages=402–411 |doi=10.1108/SSRP-05-2018-0020 |s2cid=150065703}}</ref>

Critics argue that efforts by large corporations such as [[Dove (toiletries)|Dove]] to capitalize on the movement through activist advertising<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/avidan/2017/05/11/dove-invented-femvertising-but-its-latest-stunt-didnt-wash-with-consumers/|title=Dove Invented 'Femvertising' But Its Latest Stunt Didn't Wash With Consumers|last=Dan|first=Avi|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-04-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190421142925/https://www.forbes.com/sites/avidan/2017/05/11/dove-invented-femvertising-but-its-latest-stunt-didnt-wash-with-consumers/|archive-date=21 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> may be inimical to fourth-wave feminism, which tends to be critical of capitalism as an economic system.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Annis|first=Ashley Hartman|date=Winter 2016|title=Which way is feminism leaning? A critique of Sandberg's 'Feminist Manifesto'|url=https://www.library.wisc.edu/gwslibrarian/wp-content/uploads/sites/28/2016/07/FC_3712_Lean-In-Out.pdf|journal=Feminist Collections: A Quarterly of Women's Studies Resources|volume=37|issue=1–2|pages=3–5|via=GenderWatch|access-date=2 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160909212417/https://www.library.wisc.edu/gwslibrarian/wp-content/uploads/sites/28/2016/07/FC_3712_Lean-In-Out.pdf|archive-date=9 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>

The conservative critique of fourth-wave feminism is that when women believe that the world is set against them through social systems such as [[patriarchy]], they will abandon all efforts instead of competing with men as equals. Author Joanna Williams writes in ''[[The American Conservative]]'' that fourth-wave feminism encourages women to "call upon external helpmates, like the state and ugly identity politics that push good men away". Williams also associates the movement with the "[[regressive left]]", claiming fourth-wave feminists are authoritarian and illiberal by dictating acceptable ideologies and policing the speech of men and women.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theamericanconservative.com/articles/fourth-wave-feminismwhy-no-one-escapes/|title=Fourth Wave Feminism: Why No One Escapes|last=Williams|first=Joanna|website=The American Conservative|date=4 September 2018 |access-date=2019-04-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402031653/https://www.theamericanconservative.com/articles/fourth-wave-feminismwhy-no-one-escapes/|archive-date=2 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

It is also argued that when people participate in Internet activism, they may not feel the need to do anything else to help the effort and to make themselves feel good.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Mitra |first=Zinia |title=Fourth Wave Feminism, Social Media and (Sl)Activism |publisher=[[Kitaab]] |year=2020 |isbn=978-981-18-0550-9}}</ref> This type of activism is addressed in feminist punk band [[Le Tigre]]'s 2001 song "[[Get Off the Internet]]", from before social media came into the picture. Later, in 2015, Alex Guardado asserted in an article on Twitter activism for NewUniversity.org that after contributing their say, people just "continue on with their day, liking other posts or retweeting". Some may think of themselves as activists while never bothering to attend a rally or extend their message beyond their Twitter fan base.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newuniversity.org/2015/03/opinion/hashtag-activism-the-benefits-and-limitations-of-activism/|title=Hashtag Activism: The Benefits and Limitations of #Activism|last=Guardado|first=Alex|date=3 March 2015|work=New University|publisher=University of California, Irvine|access-date=21 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503053133/http://www.newuniversity.org/2015/03/opinion/hashtag-activism-the-benefits-and-limitations-of-activism/|archive-date=3 May 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> While various feminist campaigns have spread via social media, the term [[slacktivism]] was coined to describe the mass media users who may speak out on their online platform but do little else to stimulate social action outside of their online platform.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Guillard|first=Julianne|date=2016-07-28|title=Is feminism trending? Pedagogical approaches to countering (Sl)activism|journal=Gender and Education|volume=28|issue=5|pages=609–626|doi=10.1080/09540253.2015.1123227|s2cid=148497865|issn=0954-0253}}</ref> This forms part of a greater dialogue surrounding the roles and requirements of activism in an age where communities operate almost as equally online as they do face-to-face.<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Kaun|first1=Anne|last2=Uldam|first2=Julie|date=2017-09-19|title=Digital activism: After the hype|journal=New Media & Society|volume=20|issue=6|pages=2099–2106|doi=10.1177/1461444817731924|s2cid=206729225|issn=1461-4448|url=http://urn.kb.se/resolve?urn=urn:nbn:se:sh:diva-33458}}</ref>

Jennifer Simpkins of ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' argued in 2014 that fourth-wave feminism had created a hostile, ''[[Mean Girls]]''–like atmosphere, in which women are more likely to tear each other down. "I've actually never once been belittled and attacked by a man for believing in the cause of feminism ... but women are just about lining up to take a whack at the shoddy piñata of my personal tastes and opinions".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/jennifer-simpkins/feminism-fourth-wave-became-mean-girls_b_4616597.html|title='You Can't Sit with Us!'&nbsp;– How Fourth-Wave Feminism Became 'Mean Girls'|last=Simpkins|first=Jennifer|date=20 January 2014|work=The Huffington Post|access-date=21 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160510080539/http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/jennifer-simpkins/feminism-fourth-wave-became-mean-girls_b_4616597.html|archive-date=10 May 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> British scholar Ealasaid Munro says that the [[call-out culture]] of fourth-wave feminism risks marginalizing and separating people over minor disagreements when they could serve better as allies.<ref name="PSA"/>

Women and their gendered issues are not uniform and many variations in issues are a result of related issues such as race, sexuality and class and Munro also provides the critique that mainstream feminism is focused on the struggle of middle-class white women.<ref name="PSA" /> Social campaigns that cast celebrities as the face of the movement, such as the [[Me Too movement]], have been criticized, because celebrities often represent the privileged sectors of society, which in turn negate the efforts to expand upon the [[intersectionality]] of feminism.<ref name="Looft-2017">{{Cite journal|last=Looft|first=Ruxandra|date=2017-11-02|title=#girlgaze: photography, fourth wave feminism, and social media advocacy|journal=Continuum|volume=31|issue=6|pages=892–902|doi=10.1080/10304312.2017.1370539|issn=1030-4312|s2cid=148881977}}</ref>

The wave narrative itself is criticized due to perceptions that it is only inclusive of western feminist movements<ref name="Evans-Critical-Waves" /> and that the fourth wave itself takes place in the global north, often neglecting the struggle of women in other regions.<ref name="Phillips 930–943"/> Critics also argue that using waves to define periods of feminism is no longer useful.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Radford-Hill |first=Sheila |date=2002 |title=Keepin' It Real: A Generational Commentary on Kimberly Springer's "Third Wave Black Feminism?" |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/10.1086/339638 |journal=Signs |volume=27 |issue=4 |pages=1083–1190 |doi=10.1086/339638 |jstor=10.1086/339638 |s2cid=146387753 |issn=0097-9740}}</ref> They believe there is no need for it anymore and that it can get confusing.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Grady |first=Constance |date=2018-03-20 |title=The waves of feminism, and why people keep fighting over them, explained |url=https://www.vox.com/2018/3/20/16955588/feminism-waves-explained-first-second-third-fourth |access-date=2022-11-21 |website=Vox |language=en}}</ref> The wave narrative is also contested due to the overlapping nature of the waves of feminism and the lack of concrete definitions due to disagreements between scholars and activists as to what the waves respectively encompass.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Chamberlain |first=Prudence |date=2016-04-15 |title=Affective temporality: towards a fourth wave |url=https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/09540253.2016.1169249 |journal=Gender and Education |language=en |volume=28 |issue=3 |pages=458–464 |doi=10.1080/09540253.2016.1169249 |s2cid=147625970 |issn=0954-0253}}</ref>

Other critiques of fourth-wave feminism include its lack of clear evidence in most cases of social media use. Along with this, some argue that though all issues should be dealt with, smaller issues must not be inflated to a higher level by the feminist movement. One example of this is [[Matt Damon]]'s response to the Harvey Weinstein case, "I do believe that there is a spectrum of behaviour, right? [...] There's a difference between, you know, patting someone on the butt and rape or child molestation, right?" Social media also can be seen as ineffective as it brings down "bogeyman" individuals rather than, "invent[ing] a different language or logic that can excise or alter the structures of oppression" as Sarah K. Burgess describes.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Burgess|first=Sarah K.|date=2018|title=Between the Desire for Law and the Law of Desire: #MeToo and the Cost of Telling the Truth Today|journal=Philosophy & Rhetoric|volume=51|issue=4|pages=342–367|doi=10.5325/philrhet.51.4.0342|jstor=10.5325/philrhet.51.4.0342|s2cid=149835737|issn=0031-8213}}</ref>

